One of a botanical series of small books with envelopes. Each one looks at a specific plant. The challenge of this annual endeavor is to retain the same format but introduce something unique. The printing process is photocopy. One of the pages is an original cyanotype.

One of a botanical series of small books with envelopes. Each one looks at a specific plant. The challenge of this annual endeavor is to retain the same format but introduce something unique. The printing process is photocopy with pochoir, hand coloring and collage.  Photographs are all original. Special papers include urban metal, translucent vellum and transparent film.

One of a botanical series of small books with envelopes. Each one looks at a specific plant. The challenge of this annual endeavor is to retain the same format but introduce something unique. The printing process is photocopy with pochoir done with pastel. The photographs are all original.

One of a botanical series of small books with envelopes. Each one looks at a specific plant. The challenge of this annual endeavor is to retain the same format.  The printing process is photocopy.  All photographs are original.  The image on the envelope is a leaf print, actual size. Sewn to one page is a pounded leaf print on cotton.

The world's largest effigy is a mound located on a promontory in southern Ohio. The aerial photographs of the Great Serpent were taken in 1934 by Dache M. Reeves and are reproduced courtesy of the Smithsonian Institution.  All other photographs are original. The printing process is photocopy with pochoir, color pencil and collage.  The covers are unique, done with spray paint, stencils and grass.

One of a botanical series of small books with envelopes. Each one looks at a specific plant. The challenge of this annual endeavor is to retain the same format but introduce something unique. The printing process is photocopy with hand coloring and collage.  Two foldouts read on both sides. All photographs are original. Special papers include stardream metallics.

One of a botanical series of small books with envelopes. Each one looks at a specific plant. The challenge of this annual endeavor is to retain the same format but introduce something unique. The printing process is photocopy with pochoir, hand coloring and collage.  All photographs are original. Special papers include stardream metallics.

A tribute to the all white garden through original photographs made into collages.  The printing process is photocopy. A tribute to the white garden.  The printing process is photocopy.  Images are photo collage using original photographs.  Papers are opalescent.

Quotations from my favorite artists concerning color. The illustrations are photographs of a series of my drawings. The book was produced to accompany a show of my work at the Muskegon Museum of Art, Muskegon, Michigan.

A book with text concerning the 4 elements and photographs of my drawings that coordinate. This book accompanied a retrospective show of my work at the Meadow Brook Gallery, Oakland University, Rochester, Michigan.

This book is a journey through the air and into a pond. It begins in the sky with a bird and falls from there past the water margin, through the surface of the water, deeper and deeper until it comes to rest with the organisms that live in the very bottom.The printing process is photocopy with pochoir, watercolor, color pencil and collage. Photographs and drawings are original. Special papers include ogura, ogura lace, Ingres, confetti ad translucent vellum. Covers are unique.  Each has a watercolor and was dipped in polyurethane.

In honor of Barrett Klein who has unusual taste in clothing and the personality to amuse everyone who comes in contact with him. The printing process is photocopy with color pencil and watercolor.  Special papers are holographic and Spanish dots.

Umberto Eco was quoted in the NY Times as wanting to have on his tombstone a quote from an early Italian writer, 'Wait. Wait. I can not.' To describe this feeling of inevitable translation from youth to death, I have used a group of tulips. The first is dense color and is on heavy paper. Each following tulip is lighter in color and is on lighter and lighter weight paper until the final tulip is simply a ghost.The printing process is photocopy, with woodcuts, pochoir and pencil rubbing.  Special papers include mulberry, sekishu, silk tissue and Okawara. Each cover is a unique piece of paste paper.

An eccentric history of lettuce from ancient times to today. The printing process is photocopy with woodcuts, pochoir, hand rubbings of wood blocks and color pencil.  All photographs are original.  Special papers include Indian rag with inclusions of algae, rice and straw, unryu crinkled and vellum. The cover is handmade cotton with lettuce seed inclusions and lettuce leaf watermark.

Aspects of camouflage described by words and images. The printing process is photocopy with pochoir, rubber stamps and spatter paint. Cloth pages are linen and silk organza.  Special papers include acetate, Twinrocker, glassine, kinwashi, Thai unryu and algae rag.

A collaborative effort. Different artists, poets, scientists and a dancer were asked to describe something to do with the subject of flight. The printing process is photocopy and offset lithography with pochoir, hand coloring and collage.  One page is hand drawn on notebook paper.  Another has vacu-formed acetate insect wings. A fish is printed in 3 colors. Special papers include kinwashi,Ingres, translucent vellum, acetate,shadow calligraphy and silver vellum. One artist included an extra printed sheet with stickers and instructions on how to fold a paper airplane.  The covers of the book are handmade cotton paper with inclusions of bits from the garden and feathers.  The paper was waxed and then glued to a rag base.

A walk through the village in India where the parents of our daughter-in-law live. The images are collages of original photographs, papers and textiles. The printing process is photocopy with pochoir and hand coloring.  The end sheets are fabric from a Bengali sari.  The covers are covered with hand screened Indian paper.

A story of the desert from a sunrise to another sunrise on the following day, each hour with its own page. Each page is a different paper whose color has something to do with the intensity of the light. Each image is suitable to what might be happening at that time of day.The printing process is photocopy with pochoir.  Handwork includes acrylic, color pencil, gouache, aquerelle sticks and pastel.  Special papers include Thai tissue, recycled with coffeebean chaff, recycled with garlic skins, Ingres, lokta, translucent vellum, acetate and urban metallics.  The cover is handmade Himalayan mounted on rag with a sun and moon built out of plaster and hand leafed in gold or aluminum.

Robert Graves wrote about the ancient Druidical alphabet consisting of 13 consonants. Each of these letters also represented a lunar month. Each month and the extra day, the winter solstice, was represented by a tree. Each tree in this project has a chapter of 5 pages. The beginning page gives the information about the letter and contains a quote specifically about the tree. This is followed by a poem, by one of 14 different poets, and a minor illustration. The final 2 pages have images of the leaf of the tree and a major illustration. Each chapter is under this format but is unique in terms of its materials and visual concept.The printing process is photocopy with pochoir, photocopy transfer and letterpress. Handwork is in color penil, pastel, spray acryllic, glitter glue, sewing and collage.  Special papers include book cloth, mica, super metallics, lokta, lami-li, mi-teines, translucent vellum, acetate, hanji natural, Ingres and Indian text.  Binding is coptic stitch.
